	</td>
	<td class="thead">
	
	<!-- 2 -->
	<table cellpadding="0" cellspacing="0" border="0" width="100%">
	<tr>
		
		<td class="smallfont"><b>Chapter 8.</b></td>
		<td class="smallfont" align="right" wrap="nowrap">Post #<b><a href="showpost.php?s=150f90c73d3c04d5ccf51dbd923c7098&amp;postid=9000&postcount=8" target="new">8</a></b></td>
	</tr>
	</table>
	<!-- /2 -->
	
	</td>
</tr>
<tr>
	<td class="alt2" width="175" align="center" valign="top" nowrap="nowrap"><b>Numbuk</b>
<span class="smallfont">
	<br />
	Ogre Musician<br />
	
	<br /><img src="image.php?s=150f90c73d3c04d5ccf51dbd923c7098&amp;userid=6035&amp;dateline=1034275367" border="0" alt="Avatar" title="Numbuk's Avatar" hspace="4" vspace="4" /><br />
	<br />
	Joined: Feb 2000<br />
	Location: Oggok UT, USA
</span></td>
	
	<td class="alt2" valign="top">
	
	<!-- message -->
	<p>Treehugger dressed Bash's wound as best he could, but he was no doctor.  Treehugger was sure da bandages would no last.  <br />
<br />
After a quick bath (more like "ogre dunk") in a nearby pond, Lilting was, for da most part,  cleaned up and ready to go.  Northward bound, our party trekked.<br />
<br />
Through da desert dey went.  Hot sands blowing into deir face, sand blowing down up deir shirts, sand blowing down deir paints, it was not da best ting each of dem remembered.  Da worst of it, dough, was Lilting constantly complaining about his chapped lips and how he needed some chapstick or he'd "just die."<br />
<br />
Half a day's journey through da desert, Bash started to feel da effects of his loss of blood.  His bandages had long since been bled through and dere was nothing any of dem could do but hope dey made it to da Oasis in time.  Pushing back da pain and fatigue, Bash moved onward.<br />
<br />
A couple hours later, Bash collapsed.  Lilting and Treehugger spent some time rigging up a stretcher dat dey could drag da ogre on.<br />
<br />
After several hours, dey gave up.  Dere is no way in da Plane of Hate dat a halfling and a half-elf can move an ogre.  No possible way.   So, dey just dumped some water on Bash's face and smacked him around a bit.  After twenty minutes of dis, Bash wake up enough to continue on.<br />
<br />
Barely able to lift his hammer anymore and just dragging it in da sand, Bash saw finally saw a ray of hope.  In da not-too-distance, he saw what appeared to be a small oasis.  He concluded dat dis place must be da Oasis.  Dough, it confused him because just a few hundred feet from da Oasis was da ocean, but he soon forgot about dat and concentrated on more important tings like how much a good halfling, lettuce, and tomato sandwich cost.  And how does paper actually beat rock?  And, oh yeah, how he can get dis nasty cut in his leg cured.<br />
<br />
"This is it! Treehugger said.  "We're bound to find a cleric here."<br />
<br />
"I hope so." whined Lilting.  "I'm sure to die if I don't get my lips healed!"<br />
<br />
Treehugger just gave da halfling a scornful look.<br />
<br />
"Oh yeah.  Right." Lilting remembered da ogre's big gash.<br />
<br />
"Me.... be... ok." Bash said in ragged breaths.  "It.....just....papercut."<br />
<br />
Without hesitating or arguing da point, Treehugger lead da way down near da shore to a small, abandoned dock.  Well, it was abandoned by da original owner, but it was currently occupied.  A berry long line of peoples of all shapes and sizes was formed for someting.  As da party approached, dey saw what it was for.<br />
<br />
A high-elf female stood at da beginning of da line, facing all da peoples who was obviously waiting for her.  She was dressed in a blue and white robe and had light brown hair.  She was tall, tall even for a high-elf.  Treehugger made haste to get to her.<br />
<br />
"And what's your problem?" da high-elf asked a human who's arms and legs apparently had been chewn off.  "And I suppose you want that healed, huh?  You sure?  You could get quite the many ladies with a nickname like 'Stumpy' and a tale of woe about the loss of your limbs."<br />
<br />
Da man started to frown.<br />
<br />
"Oh all right!" da high-elf said exasperated.  "Blah biddy blah, you're healed.  Now get out of here.  And if I see you again today, you're going to be 'Stumpy' for good!"<br />
<br />
Next in line was a male wood-elf who was not bleeding and had all of his limbs.<br />
<br />
"And what's your problem, little man?" said da high-elf, obviously not caring.  Da wood-elf turned around to show what was wrong.  Clamped onto his rear was a baby alligator who did not want to let go it seemed.<br />
<br />
With a quick yank and a loud scream from da wood-elf, da high-elf removed da alligator and threw it into da ocean.  "Blah blah blah, you're healed."  Da high-elf became real saracastic and condescending and said, "Now don't pick on those mean ol' babies anymore!" and den cackled.<br />
<br />
Treehugger appeared, out of breath from running.  "Ogre.... cut..... lips.... leg.... orc...."<br />
<br />
"Look, honey, I don't care what kind of panting pervert you are, but you're going to have to get in line like the rest of these poor saps!"<br />
<br />
Catching his breath, Treehugger stood up straight and finally realized just exactly how beautiful dis high-elf female was.  "Whoa!  Hey baby!  What's your sign?"<br />
<br />
"Red and octagonal.  Now get in line!"<br />
<br />
Remembering just why he was here, Treehugger focused his mind back on da situation at hand.  "Forgive me, but I am dire need of help.  An ogre friend of mine is in need of your aid or he will die."<br />
<br />
"And I should care because...?  Look, all of these people in line are 'on the brink of death' and many of them have been waiting here for hours!"<br />
<br />
"It sounds like you're not enjoying this."<br />
<br />
"Oh, I love to sit in the hot sun healing idiots who think they're all big and bad by fighting crocodiles only to learn they get the tar pounded out of them." said da high-elf sarcastically.<br />
<br />
"Well, look, what if I said we could get out of here.  What if I said I can take you to a place that is nothing like this hot desert?  We are in need of a cleric."<br />
<br />
"You're in need of a brain.  But still, it would be nice to get out of here.  What's the catch?"<br />
<br />
"My ogre friend..."<br />
<br />
"Right, right.  You're mortally wounded ogre friend."<br />
<br />
"Yes.  Can you please go over there and heal him?"<br />
<br />
"All right, all right!  I'll go.  You lead the way though.  I don't want you staring at my elven behind, pig!"<br />
<br />
"Sure thing.  My name is Treehugger."  <br />
<br />
"Am I supposed to care or something?"<br />
<br />
"What about all these people you need to heal?"<br />
<br />
"I'm sure they'll manage.  They've survived this far in life despite the fact they're idiots.  They'll continue to survive somehow.  Morons never seem to die."<br />
<br />
All da people in line began to start frowning and crying.<br />
<br />
And wit dat, Treehugger lead da way towards da place where Bash had passed out yet again.  <i>"I think she likes me,"</i> he thought and smiled.  <i>"I'm such a smoothie!  Too bad I'm going to die any day now."</i><br />
<br />
Da two approached da prone ogre and a crouched halfling searching da ogre for any sort of chapstick.  He turned around and shot straight up as he saw da high-elf.<br />
<br />
"Whoa, big momma!" said da shocked halfling.<br />
<br />
"Whoa, big intelligence!" said da high-elf mockingly.  "Now, stand back, both of you."<br />
<br />
Da high-elf removed da blood-soaked bandages, placed her hands over da wound and said, "Blah blah, yakkity yak.  You're healed."<br />
<br />
She moved her hands away and da wound was gone.  Bash's eyes snapped open and he sat up.  "Me had bad dream.  Me dreamt me was getting felt-up by Lilting!"<br />
<br />
"My lady," Treehugger began, "Meet Bash Emgood.  The little one is Lilting Lildruid."<br />
<br />
"Yeah yeah.  Let's get acquaintences over with already.  I'm Medsa.  Medsa Lotte."<br />
<br />
<i>"What a pretty name for a pretty lady,"</i> Treehugger thought.</p>
	
	
	
	
	
