<tr>
	<td class="alt2" width="175" align="center" valign="top" nowrap="nowrap"><b>Numbuk</b>
<span class="smallfont">
	<br />
	Ogre Musician<br />
	
	<br /><img src="image.php?s=150f90c73d3c04d5ccf51dbd923c7098&amp;userid=6035&amp;dateline=1034275367" border="0" alt="Avatar" title="Numbuk's Avatar" hspace="4" vspace="4" /><br />
	<br />
	Joined: Feb 2000<br />
	Location: Oggok UT, USA
</span></td>
	
	<td class="alt2" valign="top">
	
	<!-- message -->
	<p>"Lilting!" shouted da big ogre.  "Lilting!!"<br />
<br />
"I'll get him!" said Treehugger pushing his way past his friends trying to get to da river's edge.<br />
<br />
"No!" exclaimed Pyra.  "The current is too powerful!  Nobody but our big friend here could withstand the pull, and even he would be too slow to catch up to the halfling!"<br />
<br />
"Then what can we do?" asked Medsa.  She looked down at da ground and started to feel bad dat she ever made fun of da little guy.<br />
<br />
Nobody knew what to do.  Dey all kept looking down da river where dey last saw Lilting being carried away by da raging water.<br />
<br />
Yessir scratched his stubbly chin for several minutes.  He finally broke the silence.<br />
<br />
"Ye know," da paladin began, "I remember fightin' a river dragon in this here stream.  The current toppled both me and the fearsome beast this way and that, but in the end I was victorious."<br />
<br />
Da group turned deir heads listened intently to da crazy old man.<br />
<br />
"I beat the dragon, but the river still had it's icy grip of death on me.  I could do nothing but wait for the end.<br />
<br />
"Luckily, a few miles west of here, the water's flow is disrupted greatly.  The water weaves back and forth, and I was thrown onto the shore of Southern Karana.  Most large pieces of debris eventually end up on the shallow, southern end because of this figure-eight like water pattern."<br />
<br />
"Is yous saying dat Lilting is probably on udder side of da river?" asked Bash.  Da ogre was concerned for his little buddy.  But, concern suddenly shifted to himself when he realized he was still naked.<br />
<br />
"It's a possibility," said Yessir.  "We can but only search, can't we?"<br />
<br />
Bash went over to a nearby bush and uprooted it.  Sliding da bush on like a pair of underwear, it did well to hide his ogreness.  Mostly well.<br />
<br />
Da wizardess Pyra suddenly pointed to da south-west. "We can't cross the river here, but there is a bridge in Northern Karana that we could use.  It would be just a matter of tracking the halfling down once on the other side."<br />
<br />
"Leave that to me!" said Treehugger.  "I can track a falcon on a cloudy day!  Well... ok... maybe not a falcon... or on a cloudy day.... but I can track some things!  Sometimes, anyway."<br />
<br />
"Well, let's get to it then!" said an impatient Medsa.  She started off along da riverbank and headed west.  Da party immediately started marching behind her.<br />
<br />
********<br />
<br />
Life was going good for Cam-Pur and his gang of thugs.  They'd wait outside the little rat-hole known as SplitPaw and just 'jump' the poor dogs and rob them of their gold and trinkets.  It required no effort whatsoever.  This was Southern Karana living at its finest.<br />
<br />
It was da greatest time Cam-Pur and his gang ever had.  Da best time, dat is, until a female treant came storming over da hill screaming in a panic and rage.<br />
<br />
"My baby!!  Where's my baby?!?  Someone kidnapped my baby!!" screamed da treant.<br />
<br />
Cam-Pur and three friends, Loot-Hor, Ock-Shun, and Pack-Rat spun around to see da treant coming right at dem.<br />
<br />
"It was you, wasn't it?!" da female treant screamed.  You see, dis female treant in particular was berry near-sighted.  She could no tell who kidnapped her child and dese guys looked like da culprits as anyone else.  She decided dat da best course of action is presume guilty until proven innocent.<br />
<br />
Da female treant ripped through da four peoples like dey was tissue paper.  She slammed her massive trunk-like arms into one person, den she broke da neck of anudder.  Blind mudderly rage filling her body, da small group was dead in less dan ten seconds.<br />
<br />
"Where's my baby?!" da treant asked aloud.  "<b>Where's my baby</b>?!!?!"<br />
<br />
Not seeing her offspring anywhere nearby, she set off wandering in a blind fury and panic in no direction in particular.<br />
<br />
<br />
*********<br />
<br />
<br />
Blackness is all Lilting could remember.  All he could see was black.  Someting hurt.  Someting throbbed.  He couldn't pinpoint it in dis nothingness.<br />
<br />
A sound helped stir his brain as to what was going on.  <i>What is it?  Something moving.  Something roaring.  Water!  River!  Yes, there was a river.</i><br />
<br />
Da next ting dat he noticed was da cold stickyness of someting.  Someting soft and berry sludgy.<br />
<br />
Da halfling finally realized his eyes were shut. He opened dem and in poured a blinding amount of daylight.  Dis caused the throbbing to continue much harder and faster.  He pinpointed da location to da sides of his head.  Once realizing it, da pain appeared.<br />
<br />
Lilting noticed he was face down next to da river in a big pile of mud.  His whole body, from head to toe, was completely covered in da brown muck.<br />
<br />
<i>What happened?  How did I get here?</i>  Da halfling probably could have figured it out if he had a moment longer to tink about it, but a moment longer didn't come.<br />
<br />
What came was a berry large treant.  When it saw Lilting sitting up, it screamed wit delight.<br />
<br />
"<b>My baby</b>!!!"<br />
<br />
It launched itself at Lilting and heaved him right out of da muddy bank.  It den curled its big, barky arms around da halfling and held on for dear life.<br />
<br />
Da treant, wit Lilting in arm, headed south.</p>
	
	
	
	
	
