<tr>
	<td class="alt2" width="175" align="center" valign="top" nowrap="nowrap"><b>Numbuk</b>
<span class="smallfont">
	<br />
	Ogre Musician<br />
	
	<br /><img src="image.php?s=150f90c73d3c04d5ccf51dbd923c7098&amp;userid=6035&amp;dateline=1034275367" border="0" alt="Avatar" title="Numbuk's Avatar" hspace="4" vspace="4" /><br />
	<br />
	Joined: Feb 2000<br />
	Location: Oggok UT, USA
</span></td>
	
	<td class="alt2" valign="top">
	
	<!-- message -->
	<p>Sir Yessir led da way westward along da riverbank at a hurried pace.  Da squeaks from his rusty armor was almost too loud to even hear da river itself.  <br />
<br />
Da udders were right behind da paladin.  Bash noticed dat da sun was going down.  He didn't tink dey would make it to da udder side of da river before it got dark.  He also no liked da fact dat it was gonna be cold and he  was pretty much naked.<br />
<br />
Pyra was busy shooting small blasts of fire at everyting along da river bank.  Most of da  fires she created never lasted too long.  She eventually became curious about da group she was wit.<br />
<br />
"So who is the old man?" asked da wizardess to a nearby Medsa.  <br />
<br />
"Some guy named Yessir," said da cleric who was walking briskly next to Pyra.  "I guess he's a paladin, though I don't know what paladin would be caught dead with a bucket for a helmet.  He claims to be a great dragonslayer."<br />
<br />
"And what about the ogre?" asked Pyra.  "What's his story?"<br />
<br />
"None of us are really sure.  He says he needs to get to Halas to find some type of seer or oracle.  I guess there is some big danger to the lands that he either won't speak of, or isn't sure of himself."<br />
<br />
"And the halfling?"<br />
<br />
"Just your standard, run-of-the-mill, halfling druid.  You know...?"<br />
<br />
"Annoying?"<br />
<br />
"Bingo."<br />
<br />
"And what of the ranger?  He seems kinda cute.  Are you two...?"<br />
<br />
"No!" said da cleric a little too quickly.  "No way!  I'd never date Treehugger in a million gazillion years!"<br />
<br />
Hearing his name, Treehugger turned around and smiled at da cleric.  He winked at Medsa, but da cleric just scowled back at him.  Da ranger quickly raised and lowered his eyebrows twice at her, and den turned back to continue keeping pace wit Yessir.<br />
<br />
Da night set in, and when da sun was completely gone da party saw da bridge.   It was a huge ting dat spanned da big river dat seperated da northern part from da southern Karana plains.  Part of da bridge was a guard outpost.<br />
<br />
Dey reached da outpost and went inside.  Two guards stood directly in front of da archway to da bridge.<br />
<br />
"Halt!" said one of da guards.  "None shall pass!"<br />
<br />
"Excuse us sir," said Treehugger, "But we need to get across this river."<br />
<br />
Da two guards said in unison, "<b>None shall pass</b>!"<br />
<br />
"Why?" asked Medsa.  "Is it because we have an ogre in our group?"<br />
<br />
Bash gripped his hammer tightly.<br />
<br />
Da two guards looked at each udder.  Den da first one said, "No.  None shall pass because  the bridge is under repair.  The construction crew has gone home for the night.  If you want to cross, you'll have to wait 'till morning when they can guide you across."<br />
<br />
"Right," said da udder guard.  "If you want to wait, there's a room upstairs you can stay in 'till morning."<br />
<br />
"Right!" da first guard said.<br />
<br />
Everyone looked a little confused.  But in da end, dey all went upstairs to sleep until morning.  If dey no could get across da river, dere was not much dey could do.<br />
<br />
Bash got no sleep dat night.  He kept tinking about Lilting, his hammer, and his clothes.  Why had Papa Smurpheater not told him about dis hammer?  Why did it act so funny?  Bash blamed himself for losing da halfling.  Da ogre silently vowed dat he find Lilting and den find Smellybreath and bash da goblin once and for all.  He was tired of da tings dat was happening to him, and it was all dat wizard's fault.<br />
<br />
He would smash him good if it was da last ting he did, dis he swore.  As soon as Bash thought dat, he thought he almost felt his hammer grow warm for an instant and den cool of a split second later.  He figured he imagined it.<br />
<br />
Outside, da moon shown brightly.  Nothing could be heard but da crickets, owls, and occasional wanderer accidentally being squished by a distant hill giant's foot.  All was pretty much quiet, until da sound of giant wings flapping appeared.<br />
<br />
If one were watching, dey would see a giant shadow on da ground from someting high in da air flying past da bridge.  And if one were watching closely, dey would see it was humanoid wit wings and headed west.  And if one were watching really closely, dey would see dat da 'head' of da shadow was moving back and forth as if it was searching for someting.<br />
<br />
Nobody was watching dough, and da shadow disappeared westward as quickly as it came.</p>
	
	
	
	
	
