	<!-- 2 -->
	<table cellpadding="0" cellspacing="0" border="0" width="100%">
	<tr>
		
		<td class="smallfont"><b>Chapter 33.</b></td>
		<td class="smallfont" align="right" wrap="nowrap">Post #<b><a href="showpost.php?s=150f90c73d3c04d5ccf51dbd923c7098&amp;postid=20379&postcount=33" target="new">33</a></b></td>
	</tr>
	</table>
	<!-- /2 -->
	
	</td>
</tr>
<tr>
	<td class="alt1" width="175" align="center" valign="top" nowrap="nowrap"><b>Numbuk</b>
<span class="smallfont">
	<br />
	Ogre Musician<br />
	
	<br /><img src="image.php?s=150f90c73d3c04d5ccf51dbd923c7098&amp;userid=6035&amp;dateline=1034275367" border="0" alt="Avatar" title="Numbuk's Avatar" hspace="4" vspace="4" /><br />
	<br />
	Joined: Feb 2000<br />
	Location: Oggok UT, USA
</span></td>
	
	<td class="alt1" valign="top">
	
	<!-- message -->
	<p>Bash's eyes snapped open.  He no knew how long he been asleep.  Last ting he remembered was some weird dream about a talking polar bear and freaky looking skeleton.  Bash heard and felt a deep, earth-shaking rumble.  His whole body shook wit da sound.  Da ogre immediately sat straight up.<br />
<br />
Bash saw dat he was in da same cavern from his dream.  Da torch, da bed, da ice, da cavern, all was da same.  Da deep rumbling sound came again and he shook even more fiercely dis time.  Bash pinpointed da sound to have originated from his stomach.  It was den dat he realized dat he was famished.  Da big ogre no could remember da last time he ate.<br />
<br />
Bash heard some footsteps enter da room he was in.  Wading out of da darkness was da bigger-dan-average skeleton holding a huge dinner tray.  It set it down next to da ogre's bed and den raised its hand in a "thumb's up" postion to da ogre.<br />
<br />
Bash was so hungry he no cared about anyting anymore.  He grabbed da tray and pulled off da tin lid.  He set da tray on his lap and looked at was steaming on top of it.<br />
<br />
Lying on its stomach, apple in mouth, was a gnome dat had been roasted to perfection wit a light lemon glaze.  Bash began devouring da  wonderful looking meal.  About halfway through, he looked at da skeleton.<br />
<br />
"Ish dish..." da ogre tried to say wit a mouthful of gnome, but den swallowed.  "Is dis Philiac?"<br />
<br />
Da deep voice Bash remembered from his dream all of a sudden boomed throughout da room.  "The annoying necromancer?  No, that's not him.  Though, that isn't a bad idea."<br />
<br />
Bash heard da big footsteps come from da direction of da voice.<br />
<br />
"I see you've regained much strength since we last spoke.  Excellent.  Now we can discuss what it is we need to discuss."  Da footsteps came closer and den da voice said, "Lights!"<br />
<br />
Da whole cavern lit up brightly.  Bash squinted his eyes in slight pain, but dey adjusted quickly enough.  He saw da big bear and da skeleton as plain as day standing next to him in da most beautiful, wondrous ice cavern Bash knew he would ever see.<br />
<br />
"We haven't much time," said da bear.  "Swallow your last bit of dinner, and follow me."<br />
<br />
Da bear, on all four legs, led Bash down some windy tunnels dat were carved out of da ice.  Da ogre walked alongside da bear dat was at least twice his size.  Da skeleton followed behind da two.<br />
<br />
"Who is you?  What is you?" asked Bash.<br />
<br />
"I'm a bear, nothing more.  Just smarter than your average bear, I suppose.  I have many names.  To some I am called the Glacier Bear.  To others I am the White Death.  To many orcs I am known as "Squish Squish Run Away From Squish Squish."  And to a very, very small group of extremely special people, I am  known as The Oracle."<br />
<br />
"Yous is da glacier bear?!  But, isn't yous pelt needed for da shamanic totemic helm?  Me have seen a shaman wit dat!  Yous must be dead!"<br />
<br />
"Bah!  How many of those 'totemic helms' have you seen around?  There are over a thousand of them in circulation.  Many idiot shamen come down here to kill me and claim my hide for their own selfish purposes.  All have never seen me.  I almost figured you for one of those morons, until I saw your hammer... and the fact that you're pretty much naked."<br />
<br />
Bash looked down at da leafy bush dat he had uprooted and used as a make-shift un-embarrassment.  "Oh, yeah." said da ogre.<br />
<br />
"But, if dey all have totemic helms, and none have ever seen yous...."<br />
<br />
Da bear stopped.  It turned his head to look behind itself.  "Miragul, would you care to show our young ogre friend?"<br />
<br />
Da skeleton saluted da big bear and began waving its arms.  Yellow light shot out from da skeletons hands and where it landed, a big, white bear appeared.  It looked just like da Glacier Bear, but was about two-thirds da size.  It roared at Bash and den disappeared wit a wave of da skeleton's hand.<br />
<br />
"Miragul is a wonderful lich, conjurer, and good friend." da bear said.  Da skeleton, bowed.  "He creates those things to fool the idiots.  He can create one every eight hours or so.  The hide from the conjured bears can be used to make a totemic helm.  It's too bad they're not <i>real</i> totemic.  A real totemic helmet is about thirty times as powerful as the pieces of huddah they think is so special!<br />
<br />
"If the shamen would only take the time to open up their minds they may actually get a real one someday.  But do they ever even try to talk to me?  Do they even hail any of the bears they meet?  No!  It's all about 'kill kill kill, die die die, pelt pelt pelt!'"<br />
<br />
As da three peoples continued walking, anudder skeleton came running around da corner.  It saw Miragul and ran up to da lich.  Da two exchanged high fives and den began moving deir jaws up and down as if dey was talking to one anudder.  Da sound of bone scraping against bone echoed throughout da hallway.<br />
<br />
"Ah, there's Jakontiklarkiak.  A good friend of Miragul's.  It is too bad that gnome of his isn't as cool.  I had to put him in stasis.  He'll be hibernating for a good long time.  Maybe that will cure him of his highly annoying demeanor."<br />
<br />
"Me doubt it."<br />
<br />
"Me too." said da bear shaking his head wit a sigh.<br />
<br />
"Mr Bear... uh sir..." said Bash.  "What is me doing here?"<br />
<br />
"Prophecy."<br />
<br />
"What prophecy?"<br />
<br />
"Prophecy.  There are all sorts of prophecies in this world.  Some are unimportant, some are very important.  Some are right, some are wrong, some are just plain weird.  There's even one that speaks of you stubbing your toe in this place."<br />
<br />
"OW!" screamed da ogre as his bare foot accidentally kicked a protruding rock.<br />
<br />
"I guess that particular prophecy was one of the correct ones." da bear said wit a shrug (as much as a bear can shrug at least).  "Prophecies are tricky things.  They're not set in stone, and they can be changed.  But not always.  Sometimes there are loopholes."<br />
<br />
"What does dis have to do wit me?"<br />
<br />
"The goblin that killed your parents became a student of prophecy.  He found a particularly  nasty one that he felt he could twist to his own advantage.  He learned all he could about it, and took measures to make sure all the things that kept the prophecy in check were eliminated.<br />
<br />
"Each prophecy, good or bad, has a seperate part to it that keeps it in balance.  For example, if a prophecy states that you'll stub your toe, there will be a subsection or a clause saying that it's possible a big, white bear might possibly warn you about the rock."<br />
<br />
"And why didn't yous?" asked da ogre a little upset.  His toe still hurt.<br />
<br />
"That was just an example.  Besides, it had slipped my mind.<br />
<br />
"Anyway, the goblin, whom you know to be called Smellybreath, found a prophecy that worked to his advantage.  He studied the parts that could stop him from bringing it about and made sure the loose ends were tied up, so to speak.  This is where your family comes in.<br />
<br />
"Smellybreath did indeed put a stop to the things that would be his downfall.  Your father, your mother, and... your brother."<br />
<br />
Bash fought some tears back. "Den what can me  do, if Smellybreath took care of everyting?"<br />
<br />
"Ahhh... well, I think he has overlooked some  important information.  Prophecies were written by not just by ancient prophets, but ancient lawyers too.  The language is always hard to read and understand.  I think it was a mistake to overlook you.<br />
<br />
"I am forbidden to tell you some of the more important information, for such knowledge would cause your head to implode.  Sorry, but  it would.  I don't make the rules.  But I am allowed to give you a small bit of the prophecy and point you in the right direction.  You must figure the rest out for yourself.  That is your destiny."<br />
<br />
"Me understand...  me tink."<br />
<br />
"Very well.  Listen closely Bash, for it shall be spoken only once and once only.  So is the way with prophecy.<br />
<br />
<b>Ancient word, sends a bird<br />
End of world, magic swirled<br />
Born of fire, to rule desire<br />
To make men slaves, or to their graves<br />
Champions four, are good no more<br />
Born of fire, believed a liar<br />
Tricked with fish, a demonic wish<br />
Fueled by hate, will life negate<br />
Fed by deceit, destroyed complete<br />
Born of fire, champion aspire.</b><br />
<br />
"That is all I can speak of the long prophecy that the goblin uses against this world.  Whether you use it to your advantage or not is up to you."<br />
<br />
"Me no understand it!  What it mean?!"<br />
<br />
"I can't tell you.  Sorry." said da big bear as it lowered its head.  It den raised its head once again and looked straight at Bash.  Da bear appeared to have a slight smile.<br />
<br />
"Now, how about we get you some respectable clothes, hmmm?"</p>
	
	
	
	
	
